---
import ProjectLayout from "../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro";
import PCBViewer from "../../components/PCBViewer.jsx";
import PhotoGallery from "../../components/PhotoGallery.jsx";
---

<ProjectLayout
  title="Paradigm Engineering"
  subtitle="Electrical Team · Jan 2026 – Present"
  logo="/logos/paradigm.png"
  logoAlt="Paradigm Engineering"
  logoClass="invert brightness-200"
  context="Team"
  tags={["STM32", "KiCad", "Embedded C", "PCB Design", "FDCAN", "JTAG", "PWM", "Power Electronics"]}
>

  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="font-display text-lg font-600 text-white/80 mb-4">Overview</h2>
    <p class="text-white/55 leading-relaxed max-w-2xl">
      Paradigm Engineering is a competitive engineering design team at Memorial University
      building an autonomous kart for the
      <a href="https://www.autonomouskartingseries.com/" target="_blank" class="underline underline-offset-2 decoration-white/20 hover:decoration-white/40">Autonomous Karting Series</a>.
      I'm part of the electrical team overseeing schematic capture, PCB layout, firmware
      development, and hardware validation from first prototype through integration testing.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="font-display text-lg font-600 text-white/80 mb-6">What I Built</h2>
    <div class="space-y-8">

      <!-- Vehicle Control PCB -->
      <div class="glass-card p-6">
        <div class="flex items-start justify-between mb-2">
          <h3 class="font-display font-600 text-white/85">Vehicle Control Unit (VCU) PCB</h3>
          <div class="flex gap-1.5">
            <span class="tech-tag">STM32</span>
            <span class="tech-tag">KiCad</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-white/50 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Designed an <strong class="text-white/70">STM32-based vehicle control PCB</strong> in 
          KiCad that serves as the vehicle's central control unit, responsible for managing 
          braking and steering actuator commands from the onboard compute platform.
        </p>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-white/50 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          <li>
            Integrated <strong class="text-white/70">USB-UART</strong> for serial diagnostics, 
            <strong class="text-white/70">ST-LINK/JTAG</strong> for on-board debugging and 
            flash programming, and <strong class="text-white/70">FDCAN</strong> for communication 
            with other vehicle subsystems over the CAN bus.
          </li>
          <li>
            Included <strong class="text-white/70">on-board voltage regulation</strong> with 
            decoupling networks sized to the MCU's transient current requirements, along with 
            clearly labeled <strong class="text-white/70">test points</strong> on all power rails 
            and communication lines for faster bring-up and debug.
          </li>
          <li>
            Reduced overall <strong class="text-white/70">PCB footprint</strong> compared to the 
            previous revision by optimizing component placement and trace routing, improving both 
            signal integrity and power delivery under the vehicle's space constraints.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <div class="mb-4">
          <PCBViewer
            client:only="react"
            url="/projects/paradigm/control-pcb.glb"
            thumbnail="/projects/paradigm/control-pcb-thumb.png"
            title="Vehicle Control Unit (VCU)"
            description="STM32 MCU · USB-UART · ST-LINK/JTAG · FDCAN · Voltage Regulation · Test Points"
          />
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Power Distribution PCB -->
      <div class="glass-card p-6">
        <div class="flex items-start justify-between mb-2">
          <h3 class="font-display font-600 text-white/85">Power Distribution Board</h3>
          <div class="flex gap-1.5">
            <span class="tech-tag">KiCad</span>
            <span class="tech-tag">Power Electronics</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-white/50 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Designed a <strong class="text-white/70">multi-rail power distribution PCB</strong> that 
          converts the vehicle's main battery supply into the regulated voltages required by 
          every subsystem on the platform, from the Jetson compute module running the 
          autonomy stack down to the low-power embedded controllers and sensor buses.
        </p>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-white/50 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          <li>
            Implemented <strong class="text-white/70">switching regulators</strong> with input/output 
            filtering networks and feedback control circuitry to generate stable 
            <strong class="text-white/70">48V, 24V, 12V, 5V, and 3.3V rails</strong>, each sized 
            for the current draw of its downstream loads (steering servos, compute, sensors, MCUs).
          </li>
          <li>
            Incorporated <strong class="text-white/70">reverse polarity protection</strong> and 
            fused outputs on high-current rails to guard against wiring faults during integration, 
            reducing the risk of damage to downstream electronics during field assembly.
          </li>
          <li>
            Routed high-current <strong class="text-white/70">power traces</strong> with widths 
            calculated for the expected thermal load, and placed all switching components to 
            minimize loop area and reduce conducted EMI on sensitive analog and communication lines.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <div class="mb-4">
          <PCBViewer
            client:only="react"
            url="/projects/paradigm/power-pcb.glb"
            thumbnail="/projects/paradigm/power-pcb-thumb.png"
            title="Power Distribution Board"
            description="48V · 24V · 12V · 5V · 3.3V Rails · Switching Regulators · Fused Outputs"
          />
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Embedded Firmware -->
      <div class="glass-card p-6">
        <div class="flex items-start justify-between mb-2">
          <h3 class="font-display font-600 text-white/85">Embedded Firmware: Brake Control</h3>
          <div class="flex gap-1.5">
            <span class="tech-tag">Embedded C</span>
            <span class="tech-tag">STM32</span>
            <span class="tech-tag">PWM</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-white/50 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Wrote the <strong class="text-white/70">embedded C firmware</strong> running on the VCU's 
          STM32 that handles real-time braking commands from the autonomy stack.
        </p>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-white/50 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          <li>
            Implemented <strong class="text-white/70">PWM-based motor braking control</strong> with 
            configurable duty cycle mapping, allowing the Jetson compute module to command 
            proportional braking force through a simple CAN message rather than a direct 
            analog signal.
          </li>
          <li>
            Tuned <strong class="text-white/70">actuator response timing</strong> during bench 
            testing to ensure the brake actuator reached target force within the system's 
            real-time control loop requirements.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-sm text-white/50 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Here we're running the brake actuator through a serial terminal. You type in a target
          angle and the STM32 drives the motor to that position via PWM. The UP/DOWN commands
          map to brake ON and brake OFF states, and you can see the actuator physically rotate
          to match the commanded angle in real time.
        </p>
        <PhotoGallery
          client:only="react"
          images={[
            { video: "/projects/paradigm/motor-brake-demo.mp4", alt: "Motor brake angle test", caption: "Terminal-driven brake actuator test, commanding specific angles with real-time motor response" },
          ]}
        />
      </div>

      <!-- Board Bring-Up -->
      <div class="glass-card p-6">
        <div class="flex items-start justify-between mb-2">
          <h3 class="font-display font-600 text-white/85">Board Bring-Up & Validation</h3>
          <div class="flex gap-1.5">
            <span class="tech-tag">Oscilloscope</span>
            <span class="tech-tag">Multimeter</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-white/50 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Performed <strong class="text-white/70">first-power-on and electrical validation</strong> 
          for each custom board before handing it off for integration with the rest of the vehicle.
        </p>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-white/50 leading-relaxed">
          <li>
            Verified all <strong class="text-white/70">voltage rails</strong> under no-load and 
            loaded conditions using a bench supply and multimeter, checking for correct output 
            voltage, ripple, and thermal behavior at the switching regulator stage.
          </li>
          <li>
            Used an <strong class="text-white/70">oscilloscope</strong> to probe FDCAN, UART, and 
            JTAG lines during communication tests, identifying and resolving signal integrity 
            issues (ringing, reflections) caused by trace impedance mismatches on the first 
            board revision.
          </li>
          <li>
            Hand-soldered <strong class="text-white/70">surface mount components</strong> onto
            the control board and verified every connection with a multimeter before powering on,
            checking for shorts across pads and confirming continuity on all signal traces back
            to the MCU.
          </li>
          <li>
            Documented all <strong class="text-white/70">bring-up procedures</strong> and failure
            modes encountered so that future board revisions could be validated faster by other
            team members.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <PhotoGallery
          client:only="react"
          images={[
            { src: "/projects/paradigm/soldering-control-board.jpg", alt: "Soldering surface mount components", caption: "Hand-soldering surface mount components onto the AUX Control board during bring-up" },
          ]}
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</ProjectLayout>